This practical demonstrates how to build a Java web application (WAR file) using Maven, containerize it with Docker, 
and deploy it in a containerized environment to simulate cloud deployment.

Step 1: Create Maven Web Application

Run the following command:

mvn archetype:generate \
-DgroupId=com.example \
-DartifactId=maven-docker-webapp \
-DarchetypeArtifactId=maven-archetype-webapp \
-DinteractiveMode=false

This creates a basic Maven web application structure.

Step 2: Configure pom.xml

Copy and paste this file:

<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="
         http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0
         http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">

    <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

    <groupId>com.example</groupId>
    <artifactId>maven-docker-webapp</artifactId>
    <version>1.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
    <packaging>war</packaging>

    <name>Maven Docker Web Application</name>

    <dependencies>
        <dependency>
            <groupId>jakarta.servlet</groupId>
            <artifactId>jakarta.servlet-api</artifactId>
            <version>6.0.0</version>
            <scope>provided</scope>
        </dependency>
    </dependencies>

</project>
Step 3: Create Web Page

Create file:

src/main/webapp/index.jsp

<html>
<head>
    <title>Java Web App</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Hello from Maven + Docker Deployment</h1>
    <p>Application deployed successfully!</p>
</body>
</html>
Step 4: Build WAR File Using Maven

Run:

mvn clean package

This creates:

target/maven-docker-webapp-1.0-SNAPSHOT.war

This WAR file is the deployable application.

Step 5: Create Dockerfile

Create file:

Dockerfile

FROM tomcat:10.1-jdk17

COPY target/maven-docker-webapp-1.0-SNAPSHOT.war /usr/local/tomcat/webapps/app.war

EXPOSE 8080

CMD ["catalina.sh", "run"]
Dockerfile Explanation
Base Image
FROM tomcat:10.1-jdk17

Uses Apache Tomcat with JDK 17.

Tomcat is required to run WAR files.

Copy WAR
COPY target/maven-docker-webapp-1.0-SNAPSHOT.war /usr/local/tomcat/webapps/app.war

Copies the generated WAR file into Tomcat deployment folder.

Expose Port
EXPOSE 8080

Makes application accessible on port 8080.

Start Server
CMD ["catalina.sh", "run"]

Starts Tomcat server.

Step 6: Build Docker Image

Run:

docker build -t java-webapp .

This creates a Docker image named:

java-webapp
Step 7: Run Docker Container

Run:

docker run -d -p 8080:8080 --name java-container java-webapp
Step 8: Access Application

Open browser:

http://localhost:8080/app

Output:

Hello from Maven + Docker Deployment
Application deployed successfully!
Step 9: Verify Running Container

Run:

docker ps

This shows running containers.

Step 10: Stop Container
docker stop java-container
Step 11: Remove Container
docker rm java-container
Step 12: Simulating Cloud Deployment

This Docker container simulates cloud deployment because:

application is containerized
portable across systems
can run on AWS / Azure / GCP
deployable on Kubernetes

This is how real cloud deployments work.

Real-World DevOps Workflow
Developer → Maven Build → WAR File → Docker Image → Container → Cloud Deployment
